                <h3 class="subheading">Safety First: 17 Advanced Driver-Assistance Systems</h3>
                <p>Safety is a major highlight of the new Renault Duster. As part of Renault’s <span class="font-weight-700">Human First Program, </span>the SUV is equipped with <span class="font-weight-700">17 advanced driver-assistance systems (ADAS) </span>designed to protect occupants and enhance driving confidence. <p>
                    <h5 class="subheading">Key ADAS Features:</h5>
                    <ul>
                        <li><span class="font-weight-700">Adaptive cruise control with Stop & Go function</span></li>
                        <li><span class="font-weight-700">360-degree around-view 3D camera</span></li>
                        <li><span class="font-weight-700">Active emergency braking system</span></li>
                        <li><span class="font-weight-700">Lane keep assist</span></li>
                        <li><span class="font-weight-700">Traffic sign recognition</span></li>
                    </ul>
                <p>These systems work together to reduce driver fatigue, prevent accidents, and make driving safer in both city traffic and on highways. </p>
                <div class="row m-b20">
                    <div class="col-lg-12 col-md-12 text-center image-height"><img src="~/images/blogs/2026/april/renault duster/interior.webp" alt="interior" title="interior" loading="lazy" /></div>
                </div>

                <h3 class="subheading">Powertrain Options: Performance for Every Need</h3>
                <p>The new Renault Duster offers multiple engine options, catering to a wide range of driving preferences. </p>
                <h5 class="subheading">1.0-Litre Turbo Petrol Engine</h5>
                <p>This engine is designed for efficiency and everyday usability. </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Maximum Power: </span>100 PS</li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Torque: </span>160 Nm</li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Transmission: </span>6-speed manual</li>
                </ul>
                <p>It delivers responsive performance for city driving while remaining capable on open roads. </p>
                <div class="row m-b20">
                    <div class="col-lg-12 col-md-12 text-center image-height"><img src="~/images/blogs/2026/april/renault duster/speaker.webp" alt="speaker" title="speaker" loading="lazy" /></div>
                </div>
                <h5 class="subheading">1.3-Litre Turbo Petrol with Mild Hybrid</h5>
                <p>This is the most powerful engine option available at launch. </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Maximum Power: </span>163 PS</li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Torque: </span>280 Nm</li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Transmission: </span>6-speed manual / 6-speed DCT (wet clutch) </li>
                </ul>
                <p>This turbo TCe 160 engine offers strong acceleration, smooth gear shifts, and confident highway performance, making it one of the most powerful engines in its segment. </p>
                <h5 class="subheading">1.8-Litre Strong Hybrid (E-Tech)</h5>
                <p>Set to arrive around <span class="font-weight-700">Diwali 2026, </span>the strong hybrid version focuses on efficiency and eco-friendly performance. </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Based on a <span class="font-weight-700">1.8-litre petrol engine</span></li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">1.4 kWh battery pack</span></li>
                    <li>Up to <span class="font-weight-700">80% electric mode</span></li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">8-speed DHT transmission</span></li>
                </ul>
                <p>This variant is expected to appeal strongly to buyers looking for lower running costs and reduced emissions. </p>

